Face-to-Face Interviews: In-depth, semi-structured interviews were conducted with deans and department heads from teacher education faculties. Face-to-face interviews were preferred for these participants to encourage a deeper, more personal reflection on institutional and pedagogical challenges. The interview protocol explored their perspectives on the practical implementation of AI into teacher education, its value, and ethical implications for institutional sustainability. The second group included 8 academic department heads and 8 deans in different education faculties, adopting a purposive sampling technique, which selects participants based on specific purposes to answer a research study’s questions. These participants were chosen deliberately, not randomly, as they worked as part of faculties with a demonstrated interest in AI—as evidenced by their organization of AI-related seminars—and could provide informed perspectives on institutional readiness, policy considerations, and leadershiplevel decision-making in AI adoption. Table 2 presents demographic information about participants in the second study group.
